In <4558@eram.esi.COM.AU> dave@esi.COM.AU (Dave Horsfall) writes:

>In article <1993Sep20.063709.25389@cs.aukuni.ac.nz>,
>    pgut1@cs.aukuni.ac.nz (Peter Gutmann) writes:

>| What about encrypting it with a Rip van Winkle cipher?  "Here's the cipher,
>| here's the data, here's the key, send me a postcard when you've finished
>| decrypting it".

>Unless this is a kiwi-joke, does such a thing exist?  I guess it means
>it can't be deciphered until after a certain date?

A Rip van Winkle cipher is one in which you can ensure that it'll take an 
enemy, say, hundreds of years to break.  It's main drawback is that that 
same encryption will take you thousands of years to decrypt.  This has 
limited its practical use somewhat...
 
Peter.
